stylometry:
Our plans include a variety of scenarios and factors. One idea was a construction site that Andy worked for - this would be a great situation because there can be a lot of constraints for one "order" or project. For example, time/deadline, supplies, cost of equipment and labor, etc. We figured we would want to maximize profits - a construction company usually buys the equipment for the job and then includes that in what is being charged for a consumer - therefore the least a company would want is to beak-even; however the ultimate goal would be to maximize profits.
A second situation was a pet store - Andy also worked there, and we considered the services like grooming of the pets, or something to that nature since focusing on products within the store would be too broad.
I've worked at a coffee shop, and a retail store: Sally Beauty Supply, and currently a Skilled Nursing and Rehabilitation center. The best scenario of these was Sally's - each employee had to sell certain items every month to achieve reward points - they were located throughout the store or certain ones would be selected every month and set up in the front of the store and the goal was to sell at least one thing to every customer - along with this items you had to try and sell a discount card to every customer who didn't have one. Setting up a problem for this was another good idea we had. And lastly Lauren's worked for sports teams like baseball (Captain's) and basketball (Cavs), etc. A broad scenario we came up with dealt with tickets and customers and how many sold each day, etc.
